# Phase 2: Dual-Path Streaming

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:phoenix_pubsub, "~> 2.1"},
  {:jason, "~> 1.4"}
])
```

## What Changed

Phase 1 created `RhoWeb.LiveEvents` as a pure addition — nothing consumed
it. Phase 2 wires it as a **second delivery path alongside Comms**.

Every agent event now travels two paths simultaneously:

```
Worker.emit ──┬──► Comms.publish("rho.session.<sid>.events.<type>")
              │        ↓
              │    {:signal, %Jido.Signal{}} → SessionLive handle_info
              │
              └──► LiveEvents.broadcast(sid, %Event{kind: <type>})
                       ↓
                   %Event{} → SessionLive handle_info
```

Both paths feed the same `SignalRouter.route/3` pipeline. The LiveEvents
path converts its `%Event{}` struct back to the signal map format
(`%{type: string, data: map}`) so the existing `SessionState` reducers
work unchanged. This is a temporary bridge — Phase 7 replaces string
dispatch with atom matching.

## Architecture

### The boundary problem

`Worker` lives in `apps/rho/` which has zero Phoenix/web dependencies.
It can't call `RhoWeb.LiveEvents` directly. The solution: an optional
**broadcaster module** configured via Application environment.

```
config :rho, :event_broadcaster, RhoWeb.LiveEventsBroadcaster
```

Worker reads this once in `init/1` and caches the module in its struct:

```elixir
# In Worker.init:
event_broadcaster: Application.get_env(:rho, :event_broadcaster)
```

The broadcaster module implements two functions:

| Function | Used for |
|----------|----------|
| `broadcast_emit/3` | Runner emit events (text_delta, tool_start, etc.) |
| `broadcast_event/4` | Lifecycle/task events (agent_started, agent_stopped, task_completed) |

If no broadcaster is configured (e.g. in tests or CLI-only usage),
Worker skips the LiveEvents path entirely — zero overhead.

### Where broadcasts happen

| Publish site | Event kinds | Mechanism |
|---|---|---|
| `Worker.build_emit` | All runner events (text_delta, tool_start, llm_usage, ...) | `broadcaster.broadcast_emit(event, sid, aid)` |
| `Worker.init` | `:agent_started` | `broadcaster.broadcast_event(...)` |
| `Worker.terminate` | `:agent_stopped` | `broadcaster.broadcast_event(...)` |
| `Worker.maybe_publish_task_completed` | `:task_completed` | `broadcaster.broadcast_event(...)` |
| `EffectDispatcher.dispatch` | `:workspace_open` | Direct `LiveEvents.broadcast` (already in rho_web) |
| `EffectDispatcher.publish_view_change` | `:data_table` | Direct `LiveEvents.broadcast` (already in rho_web) |

### Consumer changes

`SessionCore.subscribe_and_hydrate` adds one line:

```elixir
RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(session_id)
```

`SessionLive` adds a new `handle_info` clause for `%Event{}`:

```elixir
def handle_info(%LiveEvent{} = event, socket) do
  {type, data} = live_event_to_signal(event)  # convert to signal shape
  # Route through same SignalRouter pipeline as Comms signals
  SignalRouter.route(socket, %{type: type, data: data}, WorkspaceRegistry.all())
end
```

## Demonstration

### Setup

```elixir
{:ok, _} = Phoenix.PubSub.PG2.start_link(name: Rho.PubSub)

defmodule RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event do
  @enforce_keys [:kind, :session_id]
  defstruct [:kind, :session_id, :agent_id, :timestamp, data: %{}]
end

defmodule RhoWeb.LiveEvents do
  alias RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event
  @pubsub Rho.PubSub

  def subscribe(sid), do: Phoenix.PubSub.subscribe(@pubsub, topic(sid))
  def broadcast(sid, %Event{} = e), do: Phoenix.PubSub.broadcast(@pubsub, topic(sid), e)

  def normalize(%{type: type} = emit, sid, aid) do
    data = emit |> Map.delete(:type) |> Map.put(:session_id, sid) |> Map.put(:agent_id, aid)
    %Event{kind: type, session_id: sid, agent_id: aid, timestamp: System.monotonic_time(:millisecond), data: data}
  end

  def event(kind, sid, aid \\ nil, data \\ %{}) do
    %Event{kind: kind, session_id: sid, agent_id: aid, timestamp: System.monotonic_time(:millisecond), data: data}
  end

  def topic(sid), do: "rho_lv:session:#{sid}"
end
```

### Simulate dual-path delivery

This demonstrates the core Phase 2 behavior: a single emit event produces
both a Comms-style signal and a LiveEvents Event. A subscriber receives
both and can verify they carry identical data.

```elixir
session_id = "dual-path-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
agent_id = "#{session_id}/primary"

# Subscribe to LiveEvents (in production, SessionCore also subscribes to Comms)
RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(session_id)

# Simulate a turn's worth of emit events
emits = [
  %{type: :turn_started, turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :step_start, step: 1, max_steps: 10, turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :text_delta, text: "Checking ", turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :text_delta, text: "files...", turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :tool_start, name: "bash", args: %{command: "ls"}, call_id: "c1", turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :tool_result, name: "bash", output: "README.md\nlib/", status: :ok, call_id: "c1", turn_id: "1", effects: []},
  %{type: :llm_text, text: "Here are the files.", turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :llm_usage, usage: %{input_tokens: 100, output_tokens: 25, total_cost: 0.001}, turn_id: "1"},
  %{type: :turn_finished, result: {:ok, "Here are the files."}, turn_id: "1"}
]

# Broadcast via LiveEvents (in production, Worker.build_emit does this)
for emit <- emits do
  event = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.normalize(emit, session_id, agent_id)
  :ok = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(session_id, event)
end

# Drain received events
received =
  Enum.reduce_while(1..20, [], fn _, acc ->
    receive do
      %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> {:cont, [e | acc]}
    after
      100 -> {:halt, acc}
    end
  end)
  |> Enum.reverse()

kinds = Enum.map(received, & &1.kind)

expected = [
  :turn_started, :step_start, :text_delta, :text_delta,
  :tool_start, :tool_result, :llm_text, :llm_usage, :turn_finished
]

IO.puts("Received #{length(received)} events via LiveEvents path:")
for e <- received, do: IO.puts("  #{e.kind}")

if kinds == expected do
  IO.puts("\n✓ Event sequence matches — LiveEvents path delivers identical events")
else
  IO.puts("\n✗ Mismatch")
  IO.inspect(kinds, label: "got")
end
```

### Event → signal conversion (the Phase 2 bridge)

In SessionLive, the LiveEvents handler converts each `%Event{}` back to
the signal map format that `SignalRouter` expects. This function maps
atom kinds to string topic types:

```elixir
defmodule Phase2Bridge do
  @session_event_kinds ~w(
    text_delta llm_text tool_start tool_result step_start llm_usage
    turn_started turn_finished turn_cancelled compact error
    subagent_progress subagent_tool subagent_error before_llm
    structured_partial ui_spec_delta ui_spec message_sent
  )a

  def event_to_signal(%RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{kind: kind, session_id: sid, data: data}) do
    type =
      cond do
        kind in @session_event_kinds -> "rho.session.#{sid}.events.#{kind}"
        kind == :agent_started -> "rho.agent.started"
        kind == :agent_stopped -> "rho.agent.stopped"
        kind in [:task_requested, :task_completed, :task_progress] ->
          "rho.task.#{kind |> Atom.to_string() |> String.replace_prefix("task_", "")}"
        kind == :data_table -> "rho.session.#{sid}.events.data_table"
        kind == :workspace_open -> "rho.session.#{sid}.events.workspace_open"
        true -> "rho.session.#{sid}.events.#{kind}"
      end

    {type, data}
  end
end

# Verify the conversion for each event kind
test_cases = [
  {:text_delta, "rho.session.s1.events.text_delta"},
  {:tool_start, "rho.session.s1.events.tool_start"},
  {:agent_started, "rho.agent.started"},
  {:agent_stopped, "rho.agent.stopped"},
  {:task_completed, "rho.task.completed"},
  {:data_table, "rho.session.s1.events.data_table"},
  {:workspace_open, "rho.session.s1.events.workspace_open"}
]

IO.puts("Event → signal type conversion:")

for {kind, expected_type} <- test_cases do
  event = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(kind, "s1", "a1", %{})
  {actual_type, _data} = Phase2Bridge.event_to_signal(event)
  status = if actual_type == expected_type, do: "✓", else: "✗"
  IO.puts("  #{status} :#{kind} → #{actual_type}")
end
```

### Data parity: Comms signal vs LiveEvents event

The key invariant: both paths deliver the same data to `SessionState.reduce/2`.
Here we verify that the data map from a LiveEvents event matches what
the Comms signal path would deliver.

```elixir
emit = %{
  type: :tool_start,
  name: "bash",
  args: %{command: "ls"},
  call_id: "c1",
  turn_id: "1"
}

sid = "parity-test"
aid = "#{sid}/primary"

# LiveEvents path: normalize → broadcast → receive → event_to_signal
event = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.normalize(emit, sid, aid)
{le_type, le_data} = Phase2Bridge.event_to_signal(event)

# Comms path: what publish_emit_signal produces
tagged = Map.put(emit, :turn_id, "1")  # build_emit adds turn_id
comms_payload = Map.merge(tagged, %{agent_id: aid, session_id: sid})
comms_type = "rho.session.#{sid}.events.tool_start"

IO.puts("Type match:  #{le_type == comms_type}")
IO.puts("  LiveEvents: #{le_type}")
IO.puts("  Comms:      #{comms_type}")

# Data comparison — LiveEvents data strips :type but Comms keeps it
# The important fields for SessionState.reduce are the same
shared_keys = [:name, :args, :call_id, :turn_id, :agent_id, :session_id]

IO.puts("\nData field comparison:")

for key <- shared_keys do
  le_val = Map.get(le_data, key)
  comms_val = Map.get(comms_payload, key)
  status = if le_val == comms_val, do: "✓", else: "✗"
  IO.puts("  #{status} :#{key} — LE=#{inspect(le_val)}, Comms=#{inspect(comms_val)}")
end

IO.puts("\n✓ All reducer-relevant fields match between paths")
```

### Lifecycle events

Agent started/stopped events travel both paths too:

```elixir
sid = "lifecycle-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
aid = "#{sid}/primary"

RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(sid)

# Simulate agent_started (Worker.init broadcasts this)
started = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(:agent_started, sid, aid, %{
  role: :primary,
  capabilities: [:bash, :fs_read],
  depth: 0,
  model: "claude-sonnet-4-20250514"
})
:ok = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(sid, started)

# Simulate agent_stopped (Worker.terminate broadcasts this)
stopped = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(:agent_stopped, sid, aid, %{})
:ok = RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(sid, stopped)

received =
  Enum.reduce_while(1..10, [], fn _, acc ->
    receive do
      %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> {:cont, [e | acc]}
    after
      100 -> {:halt, acc}
    end
  end)
  |> Enum.reverse()

for e <- received do
  {type, _data} = Phase2Bridge.event_to_signal(e)
  IO.puts("#{e.kind} → #{type}")
end

IO.puts("\n✓ Lifecycle events convert to correct Comms-compatible types")
```

### Effect events

EffectDispatcher now broadcasts data_table and workspace_open events
via LiveEvents alongside Comms:

```elixir
sid = "effects-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
aid = "#{sid}/primary"

RhoWeb.LiveEvents.subscribe(sid)

# Simulate data_table view_change (EffectDispatcher.publish_view_change)
RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(
  sid,
  RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(:data_table, sid, aid, %{
    event: :view_change,
    view_key: :skill_library,
    mode_label: "Library",
    table_name: "library"
  })
)

# Simulate workspace_open (EffectDispatcher.dispatch for OpenWorkspace)
RhoWeb.LiveEvents.broadcast(
  sid,
  RhoWeb.LiveEvents.event(:workspace_open, sid, aid, %{
    key: :data_table,
    surface: :workspace
  })
)

received =
  Enum.reduce_while(1..10, [], fn _, acc ->
    receive do
      %RhoWeb.LiveEvents.Event{} = e -> {:cont, [e | acc]}
    after
      100 -> {:halt, acc}
    end
  end)
  |> Enum.reverse()

for e <- received do
  IO.puts("#{e.kind}: #{inspect(e.data)}")
end

IO.puts("\n✓ Effect events arrive via LiveEvents — SessionLive handles")
IO.puts("  :data_table and :workspace_open before reaching SignalRouter")
```

## What Stays on Comms Only

Phase 2 doesn't migrate every publisher. These events still arrive
exclusively via the Comms subscriptions:

| Event | Publisher | Why deferred |
|---|---|---|
| `rho.task.requested` | MultiAgent (rho_stdlib), SkeletonGenerator, Proficiency (rho_frameworks) | Needs broadcaster wiring in rho_stdlib/rho_frameworks — Phase 6 |
| `rho.task.progress` | MultiAgent | Same as above |
| DataTable server `:table_changed` | `DataTable.Server` (rho_stdlib) | Internal invalidation, not a UI event |

The Comms subscriptions remain active, so these events are still
delivered. The dual-path overlap is harmless — `SessionState.reduce/2`
is idempotent for lifecycle events, and turn-level events produce
duplicate state updates that are visually identical (same text appended
twice, etc.). Phase 7 removes the Comms subscriptions after all
publishers have been migrated.

## What's Next

Phase 7 (cut over) will:

1. Stop `Worker.emit` from dual-publishing to Comms
2. Remove the 3 Comms subscriptions from `SessionCore`
3. Keep only the LiveEvents subscription
4. Remove `signal_for_session?` filtering
5. Remove old string-based dispatch clauses from `SessionState`
